### Active Directory Recovery

The Active Directory Recovery page was improved to separate read-only checks from recovery actions.

Safe checks included:

```powershell
nltest /dsgetdc:AETHER.LAB
nltest /dclist:AETHER.LAB
dcdiag /v
Get-Service ADWS,DNS,KDC,NTDS,Netlogon | Select-Object Name,Status
Get-ADDomain
Resolve-DnsName wiki.aether.lab
```

Linux-side checks included:

```bash
ping -c 4 192.168.1.15
nc -zv 192.168.1.15 53
nc -zv 192.168.1.15 88
nc -zv 192.168.1.15 389
nc -zv 192.168.1.15 445
nslookup wiki.aether.lab 192.168.1.15
```

State-changing commands such as starting VMs or forcing Group Policy refresh were labeled clearly and should not run automatically.

### Nora Host Recovery

Nora Host Recovery was identified as a good skeleton but needed improvement. The biggest issue was a backup path mismatch.

The page referenced:

```bash
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/host/etc/
```

But the newer Backup Strategy stores `/etc` backups at:

```bash
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/etc/
```

The page should also clearly mark full `/etc` restore commands as high-risk restore-only actions.

### Virtual Machine Recovery

Virtual Machine Recovery also needed path correction.

The page referenced older paths:

```bash
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/libvirt/xml/
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/libvirt/images/
```

But the current Backup Strategy uses:

```bash
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/libvirt-xml/
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/vm-images/
```

The page correctly included a dry-run before restoring VM disk images, but broad recursive ownership changes should be narrowed where possible.

Risky command noted:

```bash
sudo chown -R libvirt-qemu:kvm /var/lib/libvirt/images/
```

Safer targeted examples:

```bash
sudo chown libvirt-qemu:kvm /var/lib/libvirt/images/WIN-DC01.qcow2
sudo chown libvirt-qemu:kvm /var/lib/libvirt/images/WIN-CLIENT01.qcow2
sudo chmod 660 /var/lib/libvirt/images/WIN-DC01.qcow2
sudo chmod 660 /var/lib/libvirt/images/WIN-CLIENT01.qcow2
```

### Docker Service Recovery

Docker Service Recovery needed similar cleanup. It referenced older backup paths:

```bash
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/docker/projects/
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/docker/volumes/<volume>/volume.tar
```

But the current Backup Strategy uses:

```bash
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/docker/project-root/
/mnt/backupdrive/AETHER/<date>/docker/volumes/<volume>.tar.gz
```

Another issue was broad recursive ownership changing:

```bash
sudo chown -R noratheredeemer:noratheredeemer /home/noratheredeemer/docker
```

This should not be a default restore step without warning, because Docker bind-mounted service data may require container-specific ownership.

